# load all the datasets
Persons_AGE10P_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Cultural Diversity/SA2_by_AGE10P_CountingPersonsPlaceofUsualResidence.csv')
Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Cultural Diversity/SA2_by_INCPTotalPersonalIncome(weekly)_CountingPersonsPlaceofUsualResidence.csv')
Persons_DistancetoWork_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Employment, Income and Education/SA2_by_DTWP1DigitLevel_CountingPersonsPlaceofUsualResidence.csv')
Persons_EducationLevel_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Employment, Income and Education/SA2_by_HEAP1DigitLevel_CountingPersonsPlaceofUsualResidence.csv')
Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Selected Dwelling Characteristics/SA2_by_RNTRDRent(weekly)Ranges_CountingDwellingsPlaceofEnumeration.csv')
Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Selected Dwelling Characteristics/SA2_by_VEHRDNumberofMotorVehicles(ranges)_CountingDwellingsPlaceofEnumeration.csv')
Families_CountofChildren_df = pd.read_csv('data/2016 Census - Selected Family Characteristics/SA2_by_CACFCountofAllChildreninFamily_CountingFamiliesPlaceofEnumeration.csv')
Is_Beach_df = pd.read_csv('data/is_beach.csv', index_col=1)

# remove last row and last 2 columns
Persons_AGE10P_df = Persons_AGE10P_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df = Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Persons_DistancetoWork_df = Persons_DistancetoWork_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Persons_EducationLevel_df = Persons_EducationLevel_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df = Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df = Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Families_CountofChildren_df = Families_CountofChildren_df.iloc[0:-1,0:-2]
Is_Beach_df = Is_Beach_df.drop(['Unnamed: 0'], axis=1)

# reset index
Persons_AGE10P_df = Persons_AGE10P_df.rename(columns={'AGE10P - Age in Ten Year Groups': 'suburbs'})
Persons_AGE10P_df = Persons_AGE10P_df.set_index('suburbs')
Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df = Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df.rename(columns={'INCP Total Personal Income (weekly)':'suburbs'})
Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df = Persons_WeekyTotalPersonalIncome_df.set_index('suburbs')
Persons_DistancetoWork_df = Persons_DistancetoWork_df.rename(columns={'DTWP - 1 Digit Level' : 'suburbs'})
Persons_DistancetoWork_df = Persons_DistancetoWork_df.set_index('suburbs')
Persons_EducationLevel_df = Persons_EducationLevel_df.rename(columns={'HEAP - 1 Digit Level' : 'suburbs'})
Persons_EducationLevel_df = Persons_EducationLevel_df.set_index('suburbs')
Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df = Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df.rename(columns={'RNTRD Rent (weekly) Ranges' : 'suburbs'})
Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df = Dwellings_WeeklyRent_df.set_index('suburbs')
Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df = Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df.rename(columns={'VEHRD Number of Motor Vehicles (ranges)' : 'suburbs'})
Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df = Dwellings_NumberofMotorVehicles_df.set_index('suburbs')
Families_CountofChildren_df = Families_CountofChildren_df.rename(columns={'CACF Count of All Children in Family' : 'suburbs'})
Families_CountofChildren_df = Families_CountofChildren_df.set_index('suburbs')

merged_features_df = combined_df.copy()

Correlation¶

In [5]:
# sort columns name
merged_features_df = merged_features_df.reindex(sorted(merged_features_df.columns), axis=1)

# create corr dataframe
corr_df = merged_features_df.corr()
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr_df, dtype=np.bool))

# plot the correlation dataframe
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
corr_heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr_df, 
                           mask=mask,
                           vmin = -1,
                           vmax=1,
                           center=0,
                           square=True, 
                           annot=True)
corr_heatmap.set_xticklabels(corr_heatmap.get_xticklabels(),
                             rotation=45,
                             horizontalalignment='right')
corr_heatmap.set_title('Correlation Heatmap')
Out[5]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Correlation Heatmap')

The correlation heatmap shows correlation from dataset combined features.

One of the highest correlation is number of persons with weekly income 1 - 499 dollars and number of persons with secondary education level, the correlation score is 0.97. It is straightforward and not counterintuitive because it is well known fact that the higher a person's education level, the more he earn and vice versa. So if there are a lot of people with low education level in a suburb, that suburb will also contain a lot of people with low level of income

Another correlation that has high score is correlation between number of dwellings with 1 - 2 motor vehicles and number of persons with age 30-59 years.

# iterate over several values of threshold
for corr_threshold in [0.1, 0.15, 0.2, 0.25, 0.3, 0.35, 0.4]:
    h_corr_features = features_class_corr_df['is_beach'][features_class_corr_df['is_beach'] > corr_threshold]
    h_corr_features = h_corr_features[:-1]
    h_corr_df = combined_df[h_corr_features.index]
    clf = svm.SVC(random_state=42)
    scores_svm_default = cross_val_score(clf, h_corr_df, Is_Beach_df['is_beach'], cv=10, verbose=0)
    print('Using dataframe with features that has correlation value greater than %.2f with target (%.d features):' %(corr_threshold, len(h_corr_df.columns)))
    print('accuracy range: [%.4f, %.4f]; mean: %.4f; std: %.4f\n'
          % (scores_svm_default.min(), scores_svm_default.max(), scores_svm_default.mean(), scores_svm_default.std()))

Features Selected Using SelectKBest¶

In [18]:

    scores_rfc_default = cross_val_score(clf, kbest_features_df, Is_Beach_df['is_beach'], cv=10, verbose=0)
    print('Using dataframe with %d features selected using SelectKBest:' %(k_iter))
    print('accuracy range: [%.4f, %.4f]; mean: %.4f; std: %.4f\n'
          % (scores_rfc_default.min(), scores_rfc_default.max(), scores_rfc_default.mean(), scores_rfc_default.std()))

Conclusion¶

For Support Vector Machine, the highest cross validation mean score is achieved when the classifier uses all of the available features and the highest cross validation mean score is 0.8475. The highest cross validation score for Logistic Regression is 0.8654 and condition to achieve that is to use dataframe with features which correlation score is over 0.15. For Random Forest classifier, the highest cross validation mean accuracy score is 0.8405 and it is achieved when the dataframe which is used for learning has 7 features selected by SelectKBest.

The maximum highest cross validation mean accuracy score achieved is 0.8645 and it does not even reach 90%. Unfortunately, it can be said that the answer to the question "Given data that is not geographical, is it possible to predict whether a location, in this case a suburb is near beach or not?" is no.
